<br>
Farmers make little profit on their produce. Although I cant speak for most produce I know that in the case of potatoes, the average farmers gains profit of about 7-15% on their produce. The supermarket on average inflates the price by about 200%. Now by the bbc's logic, cutting the subsidy would mean that farmers get paid less for their produce, so lets say their profit goes down to almost zero percent(This brings its own problems). That may sound great... a ten percent drop in the price of potatoes.. Problem is... the supermarket still makes 200%, and chances are, it will mark up prices even further.<br>
<br>
It's all a big scam. CAP is not what is costing the average tax payer money. Its the supermarkets who make an absolute fortune, and con the consumers, that are keeping prices artificially low.<br>
<br>
So besides all the other things, please voice your concern about the disappearance of subsidies. Not only will it matter nothing to your shopping bill, but it puts many thousands of people out of business. Instead - dont buy your fresh groceries from a supermarket, but buy locally. It may be cheaper... or it may be a touch more expensive, but chances are it will be of better quality.<br>
<br>
<br>
